<section class="guidelines landing-guide" id="guidelines">
    <div class="help-header"><h2>Mouse Drift Test Guide</h2><p>Catch sensor jitter that makes your cursor crawl at rest.</p></div>
    <div class="help-grid">
        <div class="help-card"><h3>How to use</h3><ol><li>Rest your hand OFF the mouse.</li><li>Move the cursor into the pad once.</li><li>Pick duration and press Start.</li><li>Don't touch the mouse until the timer ends.</li><li>Read the verdict and the pixel drift total.</li></ol></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Before testing</h3><ul><li>Disable Windows "Enhance pointer precision" (pointer acceleration).</li><li>Close any polling-rate overlay or gaming app that moves the cursor.</li><li>Use a real mousepad — glass and glossy desks fool the sensor.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Reading the result</h3><ul><li><strong>0 px:</strong> perfect sensor.</li><li><strong>Under 5 px:</strong> normal noise, nothing to worry about.</li><li><strong>5-25 px:</strong> drift worth investigating.</li><li><strong>25+ px:</strong> sensor or firmware problem; try another surface or consider replacing the mouse.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Common causes</h3><ul><li>Old laser sensor on glossy surface.</li><li>Optical sensor on transparent mat or glass desk.</li><li>Dirty sensor lens (clean with compressed air).</li><li>Firmware bug on some gaming mice — update the driver.</li></ul></div>
